    <div class="article-page__body">
      <div class="article-page__content rte">
        <p>Buying a winter jacket should be simple: pick something warm and put it on. In practice, shoppers get stuck comparing fill power, denier ratings, and "waterproof vs. water-resistant" claims that mean very little without context. This guide cuts through the spec sheet so you can match a jacket to how you'll actually use it.</p>

        <h2>Start with your climate, not the temperature rating on the tag</h2>
        <p>Temperature ratings on hangtags are a rough guideline, not a guarantee — they assume you're moving, dressed in a base layer, and out of the wind. If you commute on foot or wait at bus stops, size up in warmth. If you're mostly in and out of a car, you can prioritize style and cut a size warmer than "technical" advice suggests.</p>

        <h2>Down vs. synthetic insulation</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Down (fill power 550–900):</strong> The best warmth-to-weight ratio and the most compressible option. Higher fill power traps more air per gram, so a 700-fill jacket is warmer than a 550-fill jacket of the same weight. Down loses insulating power when wet unless it's treated as hydrophobic down.</li>
          <li><strong>Synthetic insulation:</strong> Heavier for the same warmth, but keeps insulating even when damp and costs less. A practical choice for wet climates or everyday commuter jackets that see rain.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Shell fabric matters more than people think</h2>
        <p>The outer shell determines how well your insulation survives contact with wind, rain, and abrasion. A tightly woven nylon or polyester shell with a DWR (durable water repellent) coating will shrug off drizzle and wind; a fully seam-taped waterproof shell is worth it if you're regularly out in sustained rain or snow.</p>

        <h2>Fit and layering room</h2>
        <p>A winter jacket needs enough room to layer a sweater or fleece underneath without compressing the insulation — compressed insulation loses its ability to trap warm air. Try your jacket on over the layers you'll actually wear, not just a t-shirt.</p>

        <h2>Our quick-pick checklist</h2>
        <ol>
          <li>Commuting in a cold, dry climate → mid-weight down, DWR shell</li>
          <li>Wet, coastal winters → synthetic insulation, fully seam-taped shell</li>
          <li>Extreme cold or long outdoor exposure → high fill-power down parka with a storm hood</li>
          <li>Everyday city wear → wool-blend or quilted jacket with a warm liner</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Once you know which category fits your life, browse our <a href="/collections/all">full outerwear collection</a> filtered by warmth and shell type, and check our <a href="/pages/size-guide">size guide</a> before you order.</p>
